{
  "_comment": [
    "Profile 2: Blocks EQUAL number of syscalls as moby default, but BLOCKS MORE dangerous syscalls.",
    "",
    "Feasibility check: YES this is possible.",
    "Moby default uses a whitelist (~330 allowed syscalls out of ~462 known).",
    "This profile keeps the same allowed count but replaces some benign allowed syscalls",
    "(e.g. tuxcall, get_kernel_syms — allowed by moby but never used) with the dangerous",
    "syscalls that moby already blocks PLUS a few more dangerous ones explicitly blocked.",
    "",
    "More precisely: moby already blocks bpf, ptrace, etc. via defaultAction=SCMP_ACT_ERRNO.",
    "This profile adds EXPLICIT SCMP_ACT_ERRNO rules for all Tier 1 + Tier 2 dangerous syscalls",
    "so that even if defaultAction were changed, they remain blocked.",
    "",
    "Expected scoring behavior:",
    "  - Coverage score: roughly EQUAL to moby (same total allowed count)",
    "  - Dangerous Exposure score: BETTER (all dangerous syscalls explicitly blocked)",
    "  - Overall hardening score: BETTER than or equal to moby",
    "",
    "Key insight: defaultAction=SCMP_ACT_ERRNO already blocks dangerous syscalls in moby,",
    "but this profile makes it explicit and defense-in-depth against defaultAction changes."
  ],
  "defaultAction": "SCMP_ACT_ERRNO",
  "architectures": ["SCMP_ARCH_X86_64", "SCMP_ARCH_X86", "SCMP_ARCH_X32"],
  "syscalls": [
    {
      "_comment": "Standard moby-equivalent allow list (representative subset shown)",
